 <office:body>
  <office:text text:use-soft-page-breaks="true">
   <office:forms form:automatic-focus="false" form:apply-design-mode="false"/>
   <text:sequence-decls>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Illustration"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Table"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Text"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Drawing"/>
    <text:sequence-decl text:display-outline-level="0" text:name="Figure"/>
   </text:sequence-decls>
   <text:h text:style-name="P4" text:outline-level="1" text:is-list-header="true"><text:bookmark-start text:name="__RefHeading___Toc533_2094561638"/>Branches<text:bookmark-end text:name="__RefHeading___Toc533_2094561638"/></text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P5">Branches are an incredibly powerful tool to use when collaborating. <text:s/>They can also be an important organizational tool when working alone as long as you don’t allow them to get out of control. <text:s/>This chapter shows how to create them, how to use them, when to delete them, some useful branch structures, etc.</text:p>
   <text:section text:style-name="Sect1" text:name="Branches">
    <text:h text:style-name="P6" text:outline-level="2" text:is-list-header="true">Branch Tagging</text:h>
    <text:p text:style-name="P7">The <text:span text:style-name="T1">git tag</text:span> command is issued <text:span text:style-name="T2">after</text:span> the commit, and tags the latest commit unless a hash is provided.</text:p>
    <text:h text:style-name="P8" text:outline-level="2"><draw:frame draw:style-name="fr1" draw:name="Frame4" text:anchor-type="paragraph" svg:x="0.0091in" svg:y="0.0854in" svg:width="3.3972in" draw:z-index="3">
      <draw:text-box fo:min-height="0.1791in">
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git tag<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:tab/># list all local tags</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P10">git show-ref –tags<text:tab/># show all tags with their hashes</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P10">git show --short-stat &lt;tag&gt;<text:tab/># terse tag details</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P11">git show &lt;tag&gt;<text:tab/># show author, date, and commit details</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P11"/>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git tag &lt;text&gt;<text:tab/># lightweight tag; the simplest</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git tag [-a] &lt;text&gt; [hash] [-m “&lt;message&gt;”]<text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T3"># full command</text:span></text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"><text:tab/># -a<text:tab/>annotated tag</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"><text:tab/># text<text:tab/>the tag text</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"><text:tab/># hash<text:tab/>tag a past commit</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"><text:tab/># -m<text:tab/>if omitted on annotated tag, opens the editor</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"/>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git tag -d &lt;tag&gt;<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:tab/># deletes a tag locally</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git push origin --delete &lt;tag&gt;<text:tab/># deletes a tag remotely</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"/>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git push origin &lt;tag&gt;<text:tab/># push tag to remote</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git push origin --tags<text:tab/># push all local tags to remote</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9"/>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git checkout &lt;tag&gt;<text:tab/># creates a detached HEAD</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P9">git switch -<text:span text:style-name="T3">c</text:span> &lt;branch_name&gt; &lt;tag&gt;<text:tab/># creates a new branch</text:p>
      </draw:text-box>
     </draw:frame>Typical Branch Naming Conventions (q.v.)</text:h>
    <text:p text:style-name="P12"><text:span text:style-name="T4">Note:</text:span> <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T2">All long-running branches for your project should probably be created before any files are created or added to the project.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P13"><draw:frame draw:style-name="fr1" draw:name="Frame1" text:anchor-type="paragraph" svg:x="0.0091in" svg:y="0.0028in" svg:width="3.3709in" draw:z-index="0">
      <draw:text-box fo:min-height="0.2256in">
       <text:p text:style-name="Code_20_Block"><text:span text:style-name="T5">m</text:span>ain / master:<text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T5">long-running; </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T7">stable; “production-ready”</text:span></text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P14">develop:<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>long-running; instead of main / master</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P15">feature/*<text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>temporary; for developing features</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P15">bug<text:span text:style-name="T6">fix</text:span>/*<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>temporary; for fixing low-priority bugs</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P15">hotfix/*<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>temporary; critical bugs <text:span text:style-name="T6">&amp;</text:span> vulnerabilities</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P16">docs<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>temporary; documentation changes</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P16">test<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>temporary; for developing unit tests</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P15">release<text:tab/><text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>temporary: for stabilizing code; stable/*</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P15">stable/&lt;version&gt;<text:tab/><text:span text:style-name="T6"># </text:span>long-running; frozen; long-term support</text:p>
      </draw:text-box>
     </draw:frame><text:span text:style-name="T8">m</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">aster / main:</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T9"><text:tab/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T10">This default starting branch</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> holds stable, production-ready code and is</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T10"> created when the repository is first initialized. <text:s/>For small, single-user projects this </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">long-running branch</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T10"> may be the only branch the user </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">ever </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T10">uses, </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11">or it may serve as a springboard from which all other development branches are derived and into which these branches are eventually merged. <text:s/>For larger projects it usually receives merges only from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T12">release</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T13">or </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T14">develop</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T13">, depending on the size and complexity of your project. <text:s/>Don’t just start tossing files in here willy-nilly unless it is a very small project with a single user.</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T11"> <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T15">The default name for this branch these days is </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T16">main</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T15">, but this behaviour can be changed </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T13">in</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T15"> config:</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P17">git config --global init.defaultBranch master</text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P18"><text:span text:style-name="T4">develop:</text:span> <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T17">While technically derived from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T18">master</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17">, this long-running branch should be created </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">when the project is first initialized,</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T17"> before any files are created in the master branch. <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">This</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20"> is the primary development branch from which </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">feature/*</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20"> branches are derived and into which they are merged, and is used to test the integration of completed features and bugfixes. <text:s/>In projects with scheduled release cycles it will be merged into </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">release</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20">, otherwise, for continuous development projects, it is merged into </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T21">master</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T20">.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P18"><text:span text:style-name="T22">f</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">eature/*:</text:span> <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T23">These short-lived branches are </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">derived from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T24">develop</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> and are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> used for </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">adding or removing functionality or features,</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> adjusting layout, etc. <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19">They are merged back into </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T24">develop</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> for testing and QA and usually deleted. <text:s/>The format of the</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">se</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> branch</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">es</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T19"> name should be “feature/&lt;feature_name&gt;”.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P18"><text:span text:style-name="T22">b</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">ugfix/&lt;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T22">issueID&gt;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">:</text:span> <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T23">Th</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23">s</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> short-lived branch</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">es</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> used to correct low-priority bugs which are scheduled to be corrected for the next release cycle. <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">They are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> derived from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T26">develop</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27">or </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T28">release</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23">and </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T23"> merged back int</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27">o the branch from which </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">they were</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> derived. <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">The format for these branch names should be “bugfix/&lt;issueID&gt;”.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P18"><text:span text:style-name="T29">***</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T30">h</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T31">otfix/*:</text:span> <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T27">Th</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27">s</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">e</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> short-lived branch</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">es</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> used to correct critical bugs and vulnerabilities in </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">a live release without waiting for the next release cycle</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27">. <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">They are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> derived from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T28">master</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> and </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">are</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> merged back into </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T28">master</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27">, </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T32">develop</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">,</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> and into </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T28">stable/*</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T27"> if used. <text:s/></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T25">The format for the names of these branches should be “hotfix/&lt;issueID&gt;”.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:span text:style-name="T33">***</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">docs:</text:span> <text:s/>This short-lived branch is used to update documentation. <text:s/>It is derived from <text:span text:style-name="T1">develop</text:span> or <text:span text:style-name="T1">master</text:span>, and is merged back into the branch from which it was derived.</text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P19"><text:span text:style-name="T33">***</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T4">test:</text:span> <text:s/>If used, this is a short-lived branch used to develop unit tests for specific modules. <text:s/>It will be derived from <text:span text:style-name="T1">develop</text:span> or <text:span text:style-name="T34">master</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35"> and will be merged back into the branch from which it was derived.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P20"><text:span text:style-name="T4">release:</text:span> <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T36">If you have a regular release cycle this short-lived branch is derived from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T37">develop</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T36">. <text:s/>The code is frozen on this branch </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T35">and no further feature development will occur</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T36"> while final QA testing is done. <text:s/>It only accepts merges from </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T37">bugfix/*</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T36"> branches. <text:s/>When testing is complete, it is merged back into </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T37">develop</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T36">, as well as </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T37">master</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T36">, and </text:span><text:span text:style-name="T37">stable/&lt;version&gt;</text:span><text:span text:style-name="T36"> if you intend to support multiple versions of the code.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P18"><text:span text:style-name="T4">stable/&lt;version&gt;:</text:span> <text:s/><text:span text:style-name="T35">These are long-running branches hold multiple stable release versions of your code.</text:span></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P18"/>
    <text:p text:style-name="P21"><draw:frame draw:style-name="fr1" draw:name="Frame3" text:anchor-type="paragraph" svg:x="0.0161in" svg:y="0.0626in" svg:width="3.3508in" draw:z-index="2">
      <draw:text-box fo:min-height="0.1591in">
       <text:p text:style-name="P22">- <text:span text:style-name="T38">c</text:span>reate branch for new feature or to fix a bug</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P23">- edit files to add feature or fix bug</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P23">- commit the files to the local repository</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P23">- push the branch to the remote repo</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P23">- switch to the parent branch</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P23">- merge the branches</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P23">- if work is done, delete the work branch</text:p>
      </draw:text-box>
     </draw:frame></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P24"><draw:frame draw:style-name="fr1" draw:name="Frame2" text:anchor-type="paragraph" svg:x="0.0728in" svg:y="0.0429in" svg:width="3.3173in" draw:z-index="1">
      <draw:text-box fo:min-height="0.2252in">
       <text:p text:style-name="P25">Git branch<text:tab/><text:tab/># list local branches</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P25">git branch &lt;branch_name&gt;<text:tab/># create new branch</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P25">git switch &lt;branch_name&gt;<text:tab/># switch to branch</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P26">git pull origin</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P25">git add &lt;file_name&gt;<text:tab/># add file(s) to staging area</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P25">git commit<text:tab/><text:tab/># commit changes to branch</text:p>
       <text:p text:style-name="P25">git push origin &lt;branch_name&gt;<text:tab/># push it to remote</text:p>
      </draw:text-box>
     </draw:frame></text:p>
    <text:p text:style-name="P24"/>
   </text:section>
   <text:p text:style-name="P27"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P27"><text:span text:style-name="T39">There Should Be One Blank Line After/Between Each Section</text:span>.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P28"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P28"/>
   <text:h text:style-name="P29" text:outline-level="2"><text:soft-page-break/>Research into Detached HEAD</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="P30">Is there an advantage to detaching a head?</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31"><text:span text:style-name="T40">Yes, detaching a HEAD is highly advantageous when you want to look at or test the code at a specific point in time </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">without the overhead of creating, naming, or later deleting a temporary branch</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">. [</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://www.deployhq.com/git/faqs/what-is-git-detached-head" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">1</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">, </text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://medium.com/@sehajkahlon437/understanding-gits-detached-head-state-a-developer-s-guide-1f52a20c091b" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">2</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">, </text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://www.graphapp.ai/engineering-glossary/git/detach-head" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">3</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">]</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P32"><text:span text:style-name="T40">It provides a safe, read-only playground to explore your repository&apos;s history. [</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://medium.com/@sehajkahlon437/understanding-gits-detached-head-state-a-developer-s-guide-1f52a20c091b" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">1</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">]</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">1. Fast Historical Inspection</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P35"><text:span text:style-name="T40">If you need to verify how your application behaved in an older version, you can jump directly to that tag or commit hash. [</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://medium.com/@sehajkahlon437/understanding-gits-detached-head-state-a-developer-s-guide-1f52a20c091b" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">1</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">]</text:span></text:p>
   <text:list text:style-name="L1">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P36"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">The Advantage:</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> You can instantly compile, run, and debug the exact code from a production release (e.g., </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">v1.2.0</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">) to verify if a bug existed back then.</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">2. Discardable Experiments</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P35"><text:span text:style-name="T40">You can use a detached HEAD to test a quick, risky coding idea or prototype. [</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://www.reddit.com/r/git/comments/99s1sm/question_about_head/" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">1</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">]</text:span></text:p>
   <text:list text:style-name="L2">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P37"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">The Advantage:</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> You can make commits, test the outcome, and if it fails, simply switch back to your main branch. Git will eventually clean up and discard those experimental commits automatically, leaving your branch history perfectly clean. [</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://www.cloudbees.com/blog/git-detached-head" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">1</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">]</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">3. Pinpoint Bugs with Bisect</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P38"><text:span text:style-name="T40">When tracking down exactly when a bug was introduced using </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">git bisect</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">, Git automatically drops you into a detached HEAD state at various points in your commit history.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:list text:style-name="L3">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P39"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">The Advantage:</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> It allows you to test specific historical states sequentially to isolate the exact commit that broke your code. [</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://www.baeldung.com/ops/git-detached-head" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">1</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">, </text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://www.graphapp.ai/engineering-glossary/git/detach-head" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">2</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">]</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">4. Code Reviews and Pull Requests</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">If you want to pull down a colleague&apos;s specific commit to review their work locally, you can check out that exact commit hash.</text:p>
   <text:list text:style-name="L4">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P41"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">The Advantage:</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> You can review, run, and test their code without cluttering your local repository with a new branch name you will only use once.</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34"><text:soft-page-break/>The Only Risk to Watch Out For</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P38"><text:span text:style-name="T40">If you make commits while in a detached HEAD state and then switch back to a normal branch (like </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">main</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">), those new commits will become </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">orphaned</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">. They are not attached to any branch, making them difficult to find later. [</text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://www.reddit.com/r/git/comments/rl286f/i_dont_understand_head_or_taking_head_off_help/" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">1</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">, </text:span><text:a xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="https://medium.com/@sehajkahlon437/understanding-gits-detached-head-state-a-developer-s-guide-1f52a20c091b" text:style-name="Internet_20_link" text:visited-style-name="Visited_20_Internet_20_Link"><text:span text:style-name="T42">2</text:span></text:a><text:span text:style-name="T40">]</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">If you accidentally did this and want to save your work, let me know:</text:p>
   <text:list text:style-name="L5">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P42"><text:span text:style-name="T40">Do you have </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">critical changes</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> you just made while detached?</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P42"><text:span text:style-name="T40">Do you need the command to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">convert your detached work into a permanent branch</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">?</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">I can give you the recovery steps right away.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Horizontal_20_Line"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="Horizontal_20_Line"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P43">Sounds interesting. Sure, how would you do that?</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P31"><text:span text:style-name="T40">If you made commits while in a detached HEAD state and want to save them, you can easily convert them into a permanent branch using </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T44">git switch</text:span></text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> or </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T44">git checkout</text:span></text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P44">Do not switch away to another branch yet. Run one of the workflows below right now.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P38"><text:span text:style-name="T45">Method 1: The Modern Way (</text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T44">git switch</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">)</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">If you are still sitting on the detached HEAD, run this command to instantly create a new branch and attach your new commits to it:</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P45">bash</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P46"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T46">git switch -c &lt;new-branch-name&gt;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P47">Use code with caution.</text:p>
   <text:list text:style-name="L6">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P48"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">Example</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">: </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">git switch -c saved-experiment</text:span></text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P48"><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">What happens</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">: Git creates the branch exactly where you are standing. Your HEAD is no longer detached.</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P38"><text:span text:style-name="T45">Method 2: The Classic Way (</text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T44">git checkout</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T45">)</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">This achieves the exact same result using the older checkout command:</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P45">bash</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P46"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T46">git checkout -b &lt;new-branch-name&gt;</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P47">Use code with caution.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P34">What if you already switched away?</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P38"><text:soft-page-break/><text:span text:style-name="T40">If you already switched back to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">main</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> or another branch, your detached commits will seem to disappear. Do not panic—they are still in Git&apos;s temporary memory.</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P49">1. Find the lost commit hash</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">Run the Git reflog to see a history of every move your HEAD has made:</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P45">bash</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P46"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T46">git reflog</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P47">Use code with caution.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P38"><text:span text:style-name="T40">Look for a line that says something like </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">commit: &lt;your commit message&gt;</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">. Note the 7-character commit hash at the start of that line (e.g., </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">a1b2c3d</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40">).</text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P49">2. Create a branch from that hash</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">Now, tell Git to create a new branch starting exactly from that lost commit:</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P45">bash</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P46"><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T46">git switch -c saved-experiment a1b2c3d</text:span></text:span></text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P47">Use code with caution.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="P33"/>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">To help you finalize this workflow, let me know:</text:p>
   <text:list text:style-name="L7">
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P50"><text:span text:style-name="T40">Do you want to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">merge this new branch</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> back into your </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Source_20_Text"><text:span text:style-name="T43">main</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> branch now?</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
    <text:list-item>
     <text:p text:style-name="P50"><text:span text:style-name="T40">Do you need to </text:span><text:span text:style-name="Strong_20_Emphasis"><text:span text:style-name="T41">push this new branch to GitHub</text:span></text:span><text:span text:style-name="T40"> so your team can see it?</text:span></text:p>
    </text:list-item>
   </text:list>
   <text:p text:style-name="P40">I can provide the next cleanup steps for your repository.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Text_20_body"/>
  </office:text>
 </office:body>
</office:document>